I met someone who recently asked me this question:

"One of our competitors raised $100M, and we only raised $5M. Do we have a chance?"

I said, "Absolutely you do. Their fundraise doesn't look good for you on the surface, but they have validated your space and shown that the market can be huge."

(cont)

"But you have to do things differently. You can't compete head-to-head and do the same things they are doing. You need to find the use cases they're not addressing and the customers they're not serving."

What do you think? Do you think this smaller competitor has a chance to succeed?
Agree. Money can buy a lot, but smaller competitors can move faster and get closer to their customers to truly solve their problems.
You really gotta think about these things when coming up with a URL for your website

OpenAI's VP dodged this question:

Should artists be compensated for providing training data for AI models?

IMO yes, they should be.

And crypto solves this.

https://techcrunch.com/2024/03/11/should-artists-be-paid-for-training-data-openai-vp-wouldnt-say/

One solution is that we can incentivize artists to put their work on the blockchain and only allow decentralized models to access them. 

There are many other design considerations but aligning the incentives and provenance that blockchain provides can help solve this problem!

I‚Äôve changed my tune on AI wrappers. 

I initially thought that products that are just wrappers around AI models were doomed. There‚Äôs little differentiation and OpenAI would eventually eat everyone‚Äôs lunch.

But SaaS apps are essentially wrappers around a database!

Most apps differentiate on choosing specific target audiences and serving their needs through great UX and effective distribution. 

Salesforce doesn‚Äôt have every sales organization as their customer; there are hundreds of CRMs tailored for different size company, industry, etc.

While most AI wrapper apps will likely look very similar on the surface, the way their teams build these products to serve specific customers‚Äô problems is how they‚Äôll differentiate. 

And then these AI models can be tuned and improved for these specific use cases as more usage data is collected.

I think we‚Äôll see similar patterns at the intersection of crypto+AI. 

The underlying models of AI agents in crypto will start as commodities, and they‚Äôll be wrapped for use cases such as onchain analysis for trading, treasury management, and more. Founders can leverage open-source models to get to market quickly.

Then these models will be fine-tuned for improved performance as more data is collected over time.

One consideration is how to ensure that these agents are decentralized, but that‚Äôs a topic for another day.

History doesn‚Äôt repeat itself, but it often rhymes.

Would love to hear your thoughts on this!
